03847nam a22006015i 9780674272484DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222008mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742724847 a10.4159/97806742724842doi  a(DE-B1597)613874  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aML410 7aMUS0060002bisacsh04a782.421680921 aFinson, Jon W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRobert Schumann :bThe Book of Songs /cJon W. Finson. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tPART I Schumann’s Early Songs and the Lieder of His First Maturity -- tIntroduction: Schumann’s Criticism and Early Lieder -- t1 Songs of Marriage -- t2 Irony and the Heine Cycles -- t3 Cycles of Wandering -- t4 Romances, Ballads, and the Via Media -- t5 Lyrical Schemes: Collections of Earlier Lieder und Gesänge -- tPART II Schumann’s Later Songs -- t6 The Advent of the “New Style” and the Later Cycles -- t7 Poets in Review during the Later Years -- t8 Collections in the New Style -- tEpilogue: Reception of the Late Style -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tEditions of Music Consulted and Selected Bibliography -- tIndex of Song Titles and Text Incipits -- tGeneral Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aArguably no other nineteenth-century German composer was as literate or as finely attuned to setting verse as Robert Schumann. Jon W. Finson challenges long-standing assumptions about Schumann's Lieder, engaging traditionally held interpretations. He argues against the belief that the "Year of Song" simply reflects Schumann's personal life. Finson also devotes attention to the form and metric structure of German poetry that is almost entirely new to the discussion of Schumann's songs. Arranged in part thematically, rather than merely by strict compositional chronology, this book speaks to the heart of Schumann's music. Finson's sustained attention to performance, such as questions of whether two singers might divide performance of cycles or whether miscellanies form coherent entities, allows the reader to engage Schumann's songs in novel ways. Finson brings original research and the most recent scholarship to the musically literate public and the expert alike. This represents the definitive work on Schumann's songs and the standard reference for any Schumann enthusiast.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Classical.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674272484zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674272484423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674272484/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK